issue.title: Default namespace should be different and adjustable for each application/pipeline
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
Namespace in Bake Stage should be used as a default namespace for running pipeline, if namespace is not explicitly mentioned in helm chart templates.

### Steps to Reproduce:
We simultaneously deploy 3 different parts:
- our own helm chart to `NAMESPACE A` 
- few templates to `NAMESPACE B`
- third party helm chart packed in .tgz with no mention of namespace at all

As you can see, the problem cannot be solved with `namespaceOverride` feature in Deploy Stage.
I choose namespace in Bake Stage for `NAMESPACE A` to expect deploy everything there, if it is not specified otherwise.

When we deploy this setup, the overall result will be:
- my app will be in `NAMESPACE A`
- few templates will be in `NAMESPACE B`
- third party helm chart will be in `NAMESPACE SPINNAKER`

The third party helm chart are expected to be installed in the same namespace as my app (`NAMESPACE A`).
We cannot modify third party helm charts in .tgz and unfortunately it contains templates without `{{ .Release.Namespace }}` parameter, so the bake stage with Namespace feature do nothing.
Default namespace `SPINNAKER` it is not practical. 

IMHO, we should be able to choose default namespace at the pipeline level.

### Additional Details:
Spinnaker 1.28.1

issue.title: Feature to use different service accounts per hal accounts
issue.body:
Related to https://github.com/spinnaker/spinnaker/issues/6495 issue. 
Could we please consider adding a feature to be able to use different service accounts to connect to clusters. As this could be security issues using a single service account for all the clusters.

~/hal/hal config provider kubernetes account add cluster1
--provider-version v2
--kubeconfig-file /home/spinnaker/.hal/default/credentials/cluster1
--live-manifest-calls true
--only-spinnaker-managed true
**--service-account-name cluster1** 

Clouddriver should be able to use the service-account-name to connect to specifc hal accounts

issue.title: Stage with continuePipeline = true and multiple subtasks doesn't show real failure reason
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
When stage with multiple tasks (e.g. `jenkins` task) fails at the first task and stage has `        "continuePipeline": true`, then stage continues to execute next subtasks. As a result, pipeline UI shows error of last subtask, which is misleading.


### Cloud Provider(s):
AWS, Kubernetes(for Spinnaker itself)

### Environment:
Spinnaker (v1.26.6), orca:2.20.3-20210630022216


### Feature Area:
Pipelines

### Description:
My pipeline has `jenkins` stage. This stage has multiple subtasks:
- Start Jenkins Job
- Wait For Jenkins Job Start
- Monitor Jenkins Job
- Get Build Properties
- Get Build Artifacts

We also have set "continuePipeline: true" for jenkins stage, so we can perform some action after this stage fails.
The problem occurs when "Start Jenkins Job" fails for some reason - either Jenkins is down, or jenkins job parameters are configured incorrectly and Jenkins returns HTTP 400. Then subsequent tasks are executed and obviously fail, because required parameters are not filled in the stage context (e.g "Start Jenkins Job" did not fill `buildNumber` required by subsequent stages)

As a result Pipeline UI shows misleading error from the last task:
```
Exception

 Path parameter "buildNumber" value must not be null.
```

instead of real root cause - error from first task telling about incorrectly configured parameter for jenkins job (I redacted this message a bit):
```
Exception ( Start Jenkins Job )

__INCORRECT_VALUE__ is not a valid choice for __PARAMETER_NAME__. Valid choices are: __CORRECT_VALUE__
```


### Steps to Reproduce:
- Create jenkins pipeline with `choice` parameter: https://www.jenkins.io/doc/book/pipeline/syntax/#parameters
- Create Spinnaker pipeline that contains `jenkins` stage calling previously created jenkins job/pipeline:
    - Configure `jenkins` stage to use incorrect parameter (value not specified by `choices` in Jenkinsfile)
    - Set `If stage fails: ignore the failure` (` "continuePipeline": true` in JSON representation)
- Run the pipeline

#### Actual result

Stage fails with:
```
Exception

Path parameter "buildNumber" value must not be null.
```

All subtasks are executed:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15031715/156006399-4cb32833-0b0d-4914-a8e6-3554fc31db12.png)


#### Expected result:

Stage fails with
```
Exception ( Start Jenkins Job )

__INCORRECT_VALUE__ is not a valid choice for __PARAMETER_NAME__. Valid choices are: __CORRECT_VALUE__
```

Subsequent subtasks are not executed:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15031715/156006441-98e39533-e9ba-4758-9773-b692134691ad.png)


### Additional Details:

-  When I set `continuePipeline: false`, then jenkins stage displays correct error from `Start Jenkins Job` and subsequent task are not executed. However that's not acceptable workaround, because then I can't run subsequent stages that contain error handling.

-  I think the root of the problem is mapping of STAGE behaviour to TASK behaviour here:
https://github.com/spinnaker/orca/blob/730b076879a517cd0307f55a15ca59ae00a260d5/orca-kotlin/src/main/kotlin/com/netflix/spinnaker/orca/ext/Stage.kt#L131-L137

issue.title: Feature request - use Namespace as a deployment target rather than a bake value
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

Helm builds are not immutable.

Deployed helm charts cannot include dependencies without alteration.

### Cloud Provider(s):

All

### Environment:

Kubernetes deploys

### Feature Area:

Chart baking

### Description:

Deployment to a target Kubernetes namespace is achieved by adding {{ .Release.Namespace }} to each template, enabling Spinnaker to add the predetermined namespace into the templates at the bake stage.

This presents numerous issues:

1. You have to add Release.Namespace to each chart

2. Having to modify third party chart dependencies to add Release.Namespace to their charts too (and therefore not being able to consume these dependencies without alteration)

3. Spinnaker builds are not immutable.

So... feature request - could you treat the namespace as a _target_ for any given pipeline deploy, rather than a _value_ that is baked into the charts

i.e.

helm upgrade --install release-name chart -n TARGET_NAMESPACE

Doing so would make the helm builds immutable and would remove the necessity to alter charts & their dependencies.

Templates without {{ .Release.Namespace }} interestingly do not end up in the default namespace - which you'd expect if no namespace was provided as a target during deploy - they end up in 'foo-spinnaker ' . This means that spinnaker _is_ providing a namespace during deploy, just not the namespace specified in the pipeline config.   This to me seems like a bug.


### Steps to Reproduce:

Try to deploy a  helm chart and again with dependencies

### Additional Details:

---

**_Please delete the instructions below this line prior to submitting_**

issue.title: Kustomise engine fails to render CronJob
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

When using `Bake (Manifest)` to build CronJob with overlay, instead of adding properties to container, they get overwritten. This is not what standalone/kubectl Kustomize does.

### Environment:

Spinnaker 1.26.7, KUSTOMIZE render engine, artifact from execution context.

Local kubectl version:
Client Version: version.Info{Major:"1", Minor:"24", GitVersion:"v1.24.2", GitCommit:"f66044f4361b9f1f96f0053dd46cb7dce5e990a8", GitTreeState:"clean", BuildDate:"2022-06-15T14:22:29Z", GoVersion:"go1.18.3", Compiler:"gc", Platform:"linux/amd64"}
Kustomize Version: v4.5.4


### Description:

Standalone Kustomize output:

```
apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: CronJob
metadata:
  name: cronName
spec:
  jobTemplate:
    spec:
      template:
        spec:
          containers:
          - image: hello-world
            imagePullPolicy: Always
            name: containerName
  schedule: '* * * * *'

```

Spinnaker baked output:

```
apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: CronJob
metadata:
  name: cronName
spec:
  jobTemplate:
    spec:
      template:
        spec:
          containers:
          - imagePullPolicy: Always
            name: containerName
  schedule: '* * * * *'
```

### Steps to Reproduce:

base/kustomization.yaml:
```
resources:
  - cronjob.yaml
```

base/cronjob.yaml:
```
apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: CronJob
metadata:
  name: cronName
spec:
  jobTemplate:
    spec:
      template:
        spec:
          containers:
          - name: containerName

issue.title: Using non-alphanumeric characters in an SSL cert passphrase prevents deck from loading.
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

Using non-alphanumeric characters in an SSL cert passphrase prevents deck from loading, getting stuck in a `CrashLoopBackOff` state.

### Environment:

K8s distributed

### Feature Area:
Deck
SSL

### Description:

When using the following password for an ssl cert:

```
export DECK_KEY_PASSWORD='1?Zu7,i6%4@m0]&5>j9(q3.'
```

the `/etc/apache2/passphrase` file generated in the `deck` container of the `spin-deck-*-*` pod is incorrect:

```
#!/usr/bin/env bash

if [ -n "1?Zu7,i6%4@m0]{%PASSPHRASE%}5>j9(q3." ]; then
  echo "1?Zu7,i6%4@m0]{%PASSPHRASE%}5>j9(q3."
fi
```

This password was generated from a PWM that uses all characters in the generated passwords. Ideally the docs would warn against using non-alphanumeric characters in passwords if this is expected behavior or unavoidable.
it appears to be the `&` character in particular that is causing the issue.


This is easily worked around but it took me non-significant amount of time to figure the issue out, and i imagine others could encounter the same situation.
Thanks for your time.

issue.title: %252C isn't un-escaped in spinnaker UI while %252c is
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
`https://spinnaker_hostname/#/applications/myapp/executions?pipeline=Deploy%20something%252C%20otherthing`
Resolves to `PIPELINE: Deploy something%2C otherthing`
while
`https://spinnaker_hostname/#/applications/myapp/executions?pipeline=Deploy%20something%252c%20otherthing`
Resolves to `PIPELINE: Deploy something, otherthing`

One issue is that double-escaping is needed for comma `,` but not for space ` ` character.
Another issue is that `%2C` doesn't work while `%2c` works.

https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986#section-2.1
>    The uppercase hexadecimal digits 'A' through 'F' are equivalent to
   the lowercase digits 'a' through 'f', respectively.  If two URIs
   differ only in the case of hexadecimal digits used in percent-encoded
   octets, they are equivalent.  For consistency, URI producers and
   normalizers should use uppercase hexadecimal digits for all percent-

issue.title: Deck assumes pipeline templates are only stored in Front50
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
When editing a pipeline sourced from a template using the "Configure Template" button, the changes error out since it can't find the pipeline template in front50.


### Cloud Provider(s):
AWS, Kubernetes(for Spinnaker itself)

### Environment:
Spinnaker 1.26.6, Deck 3.7.3-20211116020328

### Feature Area:
Pipeline Templates/ UI

### Description:
We use an http artifact account to grab our pipeline template JSONs from a webserver. This works quite well when referencing it in the pipeline JSON like:
```
"template": {
    "artifactAccount": "http",
    "name": "myTemplate",
    "reference": "https://example.com:443/spinnaker-templates/myTemplate.json",
    "type": "http/file"
  },
```
However when trying to update the pipeline variables via the "Configure Template" button, the updates are not saved and you see an error 
``` 
Could not generate pipeline from provided template configuration.

Error: No message provided
```

In the browser network tab we can see that the request to `https://my-spinnanker-api.com/v2/pipelineTemplates/plan` uses the below artifactAccount

```
{
    "artifactAccount": "front50ArtifactCredentials",
    "reference": "spinnaker://https://example.com:443/spinnaker-templates/myTemplate.json",
    "type": "front50/pipelineTemplate"
}
```
The expectation is that the request uses the same artifact account as the template block and successfully updates the template variables.  Note that updating the variables via "Edit Pipeline as JSON" has the desired effect and leaves the pipeline template artifact alone.


### Steps to Reproduce:
1. host a pipeline template json on a webserver
2. Create a pipeline with template block like:
"template": {
    "artifactAccount": "http",
    "name": "myTemplate",
    "reference": "https://example.com:443/spinnaker-templates/myTemplate.json",
    "type": "http/file"
  },
3. In the UI, go to configure pipeline
4. Click configure template
5. Edit one of the pipeline variables
6. Save changes
7. Notice error message and the pipeline fails to update.

issue.title: Application prefix permissions don't work with Kubernetes account + SAML authentication
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
Application prefix permissions don't work with Kubernetes + SAML authentication (not sure if the SAML authentication is relevant)

### Cloud Provider(s):
Kubernetes

### Environment:
Spinnaker is installed on a k8s cluster using this helm chart (using Spinnaker version 1.26.7): https://github.com/OpsMx/spinnaker-helm
The Spinnaker components versions are the following:
```
Spinnaker: 1.26.7
Halyard: 1.41.0
Fiat: 1.16.0
Clouddriver: 8.0.4
Deck: 3.7.2
Front50: 0.27.1
Gate: 1.22.2
Igor: 1.16.0
Orca: 2.20.3
Rosco: 0.25.0
Echo: 2.17.1
```
I've setup Spinnaker to use SAML authentication/authorization with Azure AD groups.

These are the permissions for the default Kubernetes account (taken from `hal config` command):
```yaml
name: default
version: 1.26.7
providers:
  kubernetes:
    enabled: true
    accounts:
    - name: default
      requiredGroupMembership: []
      permissions:
        READ:
        - cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c
        - 7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138
        WRITE:
        - cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c
        - 7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138
      dockerRegistries:
      - accountName: dockerhub
        namespaces: []
      providerVersion: V2
      context: default
      configureImagePullSecrets: true
      serviceAccount: true
      cacheThreads: 1
      namespaces: []
      omitNamespaces:
      - kube-system
      - kube-public
      kinds: []
      omitKinds: []
      customResources: []
      cachingPolicies: []
      rawResourcesEndpointConfig:
        kindExpressions: []
        omitKindExpressions: []
      oAuthScopes: []
      onlySpinnakerManaged: false
```


### Feature Area:
Application permissions using prefixes

### Description:
Hello, I'm new to Spinnaker and I've been trying to get the prefix application permissions work but I am not able to. No applications are shown in the UI although they match the prefix. Below the SAML group `cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c` is an admin group, the issue is with users from the `7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138` group.

Test 1 is my desired setup. Test 2 is a modification of Test 1 with capitalized application name (after looking into the Fiat source code). And Test 3 just shows that if I don't use the prefixes but exact application name, things work (but that isn't what I want)

## Test 1 - using a prefix, application with lower case - doesn't work
This is my desired setup.

The contents of the `fiat-local.yml` file is this:
```yaml
fiat:
  executeFallback: WRITE
  restrictApplicationCreation: true
  admin:
    roles:
    - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
auth:
  permissions:
    provider:
      application: aggregate
    source:
      application:
        front50:
          enabled: true
        prefix:
          enabled: true
          prefixes:
          - prefix: '*'
            permissions:
              WRITE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              CREATE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              EXECUTE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              READ:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
          - prefix: 'myapp*'
            permissions:
              READ:
              - '7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138'
```

I deployed a test k8s deployment inside the default Kubernetes account (where Spinnaker is installed) with appropriate moniker annotations for `myapplication` application:
```yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: spinnakertest-nginx-deployment-01
  namespace: spinnakertest-ns
  labels:
    app: nginx-01
  annotations:
    moniker.spinnaker.io/application: myapplication
    moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: nginx-01
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: nginx-01
      annotations:
        moniker.spinnaker.io/application: myapplication
        moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx-01
        image: nginx:1.14.2
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
```

But the users from the SAML group `7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138` can't see the app in the Spinnaker UI:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15890495/183103507-d1fff101-9137-46bb-a037-f62a81c349fd.png)

## Test 2 - using a prefix, application with upper case - doesn't work

I went through Fiat's code and found that the prefix check uses a toUpperCase(): https://github.com/spinnaker/fiat/blob/v1.16.0/fiat-roles/src/main/java/com/netflix/spinnaker/fiat/providers/ResourcePrefixPermissionSource.java#L70
```java
public boolean contains(T resource) {
  if (isFullApplicationName) {
    return prefix.equalsIgnoreCase(resource.getName());
  }

  String prefixWithoutStar = prefix.substring(0, prefix.length() - 1);
  prefixWithoutStar = prefixWithoutStar.toUpperCase();
  return resource.getName().startsWith(prefixWithoutStar);
}
```

So I changed my test k8s deployment so that the application is with capital letters:
```yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: spinnakertest-nginx-deployment-01
  namespace: spinnakertest-ns
  labels:
    app: nginx-01
  annotations:
    moniker.spinnaker.io/application: MYAPPLICATION
    moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: nginx-01
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: nginx-01
      annotations:
        moniker.spinnaker.io/application: MYAPPLICATION
        moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx-01
        image: nginx:1.14.2
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
```

This time the users from the SAML group `7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138` can see the application in the Spinnaker UI, but when I go into the application details, no details/server groups are shown:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15890495/183103728-db10b549-61db-4434-983b-22a699c7928a.png)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15890495/183103852-6c835f55-f436-4dc5-a9d7-7e0a4ec3f020.png)

## Test 3 - using exact application name (not using a prefix), application with lower case - works
This works, but it's not a desired setup - the prefixes aren't used.

When I change the prefix application permissions to contain the whole name without `*`, then everything works fine - I can see the application in the Spinnaker UI, and the details/server groups show fine as well:
`fiat-local.yaml`:
```yaml
fiat:
  executeFallback: WRITE
  restrictApplicationCreation: true
  admin:
    roles:
    - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'         
auth:
  permissions:
    provider:
      application: aggregate
    source:
      application:
        front50:
          enabled: true
        prefix:
          enabled: true
          prefixes:
          - prefix: '*'
            permissions:
              WRITE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              CREATE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              EXECUTE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              READ:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
          - prefix: 'myapplication'
            permissions:
              READ:
              - '7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138'
```
Test deployment:
```yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: spinnakertest-nginx-deployment-01
  namespace: spinnakertest-ns
  labels:
    app: nginx-01
  annotations:
    moniker.spinnaker.io/application: myapplication
    moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: nginx-01
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: nginx-01
      annotations:
        moniker.spinnaker.io/application: myapplication
        moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx-01
        image: nginx:1.14.2
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
```
Result:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15890495/183104004-d46064d2-46bd-4b47-806c-4a3993b5fd4f.png)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15890495/183104155-845d0c7d-04b7-4bbb-af7d-945b58da308b.png)

That's why I thought there might be a bug with the prefix permissions (possibly when used together with applications in a Kubernetes account + SAML authentication) - maybe the [above code snippet](https://github.com/spinnaker/fiat/blob/v1.16.0/fiat-roles/src/main/java/com/netflix/spinnaker/fiat/providers/ResourcePrefixPermissionSource.java#L70) in Fiat should be changed so case is ignored when using `String.startsWith()`, instead of having a `toUpperCase()` on just the prefix?

Or maybe I haven't configured the prefix permissions correctly?

I haven't tested it with Spinnaker 1.27.0 (Fiat version 1.28.4), because it doesn't work with the helm chart (for example these issues: https://github.com/spinnaker/spinnaker/issues/6655 , https://github.com/spinnaker/spinnaker/issues/6700 , also there are issues with the readiness probes), but I see Fiat v1.28.4 still has the same toUpperCase() code: https://github.com/spinnaker/fiat/blob/v1.28.4/fiat-roles/src/main/java/com/netflix/spinnaker/fiat/providers/ResourcePrefixPermissionSource.java#L71

### Steps to Reproduce:
Deploy Spinnaker in Kubernetes using the helm chart (https://github.com/OpsMx/spinnaker-helm). And use the above permission settings and test Kubernetes deployments (between the test cases delete the Kubernetes deployment before creating the new one to avoid leftover ReplicaSets with the old moniker application name - this adds additional issues). I'm not sure if SAML authentication/authorization is relevant.

issue.title: Clouddriver: stops syncing Docker registry at intermittent intervals
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

Potentially related issue: #4780

Clouddriver will stop syncing with our Docker registry at intermittent intervals. There is no error message logged by Clouddriver, event after setting the log level to `TRACE`.

### Cloud Provider(s):

AWS EKS

### Environment:

- EKS v1.18
- Halyard 1.40.0
- Spinnaker 1.23.3
- Clouddriver 7.0.3

### Feature Area:

Clouddriver

### Description:

### Steps to Reproduce:

### Additional Details:

When working correctly, Clouddriver will output a info message stating that it is going to start describing the cached items in the registry, and follow up with the amount of ids and tags it grabs:

```
2020-12-14 07:01:10.838  INFO 1 --- [cutionAction-29] .d.r.p.a.DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent : Describing items in <docker-registry>/DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent[1/1]
2020-12-14 07:01:13.103  INFO 1 --- [cutionAction-29] .d.r.p.a.DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent : Caching 21174 tagged images in <docker-registry>/DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent[1/1]
2020-12-14 07:01:13.103  INFO 1 --- [cutionAction-29] .d.r.p.a.DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent : Caching 21174 image ids in <docker-registry>/DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent[1/1]
```

However, I've noticed that after Clouddriver stops syncing the registry, the cached tags and ids are not printing, and we only get the message from the describe call:
```
2020-12-13 08:09:57.750  INFO 1 --- [utionAction-116] .d.r.p.a.DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent : Describing items in <docker-registry>/DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent[1/1]
```
From this point onwards, Clouddriver will not sync with the registry until it (Clouddriver) has been restarted. Once it has been restarted, it will sync with the registry just fine until this intermittent failure occurs again.

It seems like if there is a problem here with Clouddriver proper, the offending code would be somewhere in the `buildCacheResult` method of the `DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent`: https://github.com/spinnaker/clouddriver/blob/874cef3644c826a1932d9670d59ccb77a19e19a2/clouddriver-docker/src/main/groovy/com/netflix/spinnaker/clouddriver/docker/registry/provider/agent/DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent.groovy#L135

I have also checked connectivity to our Docker registry during these outages, and I can connect to it just fine while this issue occurs with Clouddriver.

fix(pipelineTriggers): handle invalid constraint regexes (#1209)

* fix(pipelineTriggers): handle invalid constraint regexes

Currently, if a user accidentally configures a pipeline trigger with an
invalid regex for a constraint value, echo throws a
`PatternSyntaxException` any time it receives an event that should be
tested against the constraint.  As a result, all pipeline triggers using
the same trigger type & source/subscription will be non-functional, not
just the pipeline with the bad regex.

This patch catches `PatternSyntaxException`, logs an error about the bad
regex for troubleshooting purposes, and returns `false` such that the
bad regex will never match, allowing all other pipeline triggers to
continue functioning normally.

issue.title: Select Clouddriver service by cloud provider
issue.body:
### Feature Area:
Kork, Orca, Gate

### Description:
It would be useful to be able to have Orca send tasks to different Clouddriver instances based upon what cloud provider the task is for. For example, having a set of Clouddriver instances that can handle Cloud Foundry tasks and another that can handle Kubernetes tasks.

### Additional Details:
We should be able to extend the Kork [SelectableService](https://github.com/spinnaker/kork/blob/master/kork-web/src/main/java/com/netflix/spinnaker/kork/web/selector/SelectableService.java) class to include cloud provider as a criteria.

Once done we can update Orca's [ExecutionContext](https://github.com/spinnaker/orca/blob/7fabdf8af372c6415fbbe1f2ba3d7a695261ebee/orca-queue/src/main/kotlin/com/netflix/spinnaker/orca/q/handler/AuthenticationAware.kt) to include the cloud provider of the current stage (if applicable), and update the [DelegatingClouddriverService](https://github.com/spinnaker/orca/blob/7fabdf8af372c6415fbbe1f2ba3d7a695261ebee/orca-clouddriver/src/main/java/com/netflix/spinnaker/orca/clouddriver/DelegatingClouddriverService.java) to include it as a criteria when selecting.

I'm unsure if changes to Gate are necessary for this. Would we need to ensure that any call, for say a specific server group, goes to a Clouddriver that can handle that provider should a cache miss happen? 

It may be more tricky because the selector today only considers the X-SPINNAKER headers, so we'd need to refactor this or include the provider(s) as a header.

issue.title: bug(artifacts): Expected Artifacts should be trigger specific
issue.body: When setting up multiple triggers with different expected artifacts, triggering the pipeline fails if _any_ defined expected artifact is missing, even if it is defined on another trigger. This fix filters the list of expected artifacts to make sure only the artifacts that are relevant for the current trigger is evaluated.

issue.title: Made pipeline creation a synchronized process to prevent from creatin…
issue.body:
We've noticed that sometimes spinnaker users end up with duplicated pipelines when using pipelines as a code. In my opinion method that validates pipeline definition and duplicates is not thread safe. When multiple threads are running the same code, it's likely that validation will pass for either of them and we will end up with duplicates.

This simple fix prevents from aforementioned scenario.

issue.title: Waiting executions doesn't follow FIFO
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
Waiting executions doesn't follow FIFO

### Cloud Provider(s):


### Environment:
Spinnaker 1.21.4, Spinnaker 1.25

### Feature Area:
Orca queue

### Description:
The sequence of queued executions, which should follow FIFO,  gets messed up when two conditions are met
1. The pipeline has branches.  When one branch completes, the running execution is waiting for other branches to complete.
2. Pipeline disables concurrent executions. So several pending executions are waiting in a queue when pipeline has running executions. 

Checked redis queue, the order of 01F0WQV9NR65J9F9N2FWN8FRVK is changed from oldest to newest. And the attempts attribute get +1
```
127.0.0.1:6379> LRANGE orca.pipeline.queue.8b4f6fbf-df5b-4ac9-9b0e-a63b3dd38c97 0 10
1) "{\"kind\":\"startExecution\",\"executionType\":\"PIPELINE\",\"executionId\":\"01F0WQVEY9XK52Y47W2DD1F91W\",\"application\":\"issuedebug\",\"attributes\":[{\"kind\":\"attempts\",\"attempts\":1}]}"
2) "{\"kind\":\"startExecution\",\"executionType\":\"PIPELINE\",\"executionId\":\"01F0WQVCB8EPRJAJNQ55VF3QTN\",\"application\":\"issuedebug\",\"attributes\":[{\"kind\":\"attempts\",\"attempts\":1}]}"
3) "{\"kind\":\"startExecution\",\"executionType\":\"PIPELINE\",\"executionId\":\"01F0WQV9NR65J9F9N2FWN8FRVK\",\"application\":\"issuedebug\",\"attributes\":[{\"kind\":\"attempts\",\"attempts\":1}]}"
127.0.0.1:6379> 
127.0.0.1:6379> 
127.0.0.1:6379> LRANGE orca.pipeline.queue.8b4f6fbf-df5b-4ac9-9b0e-a63b3dd38c97 0 10
1) "{\"kind\":\"startExecution\",\"executionType\":\"PIPELINE\",\"executionId\":\"01F0WQV9NR65J9F9N2FWN8FRVK\",\"application\":\"issuedebug\",\"attributes\":[{\"kind\":\"attempts\",\"attempts\":2}]}"
2) "{\"kind\":\"startExecution\",\"executionType\":\"PIPELINE\",\"executionId\":\"01F0WQVEY9XK52Y47W2DD1F91W\",\"application\":\"issuedebug\",\"attributes\":[{\"kind\":\"attempts\",\"attempts\":1}]}"
3) "{\"kind\":\"startExecution\",\"executionType\":\"PIPELINE\",\"executionId\":\"01F0WQVCB8EPRJAJNQ55VF3QTN\",\"application\":\"issuedebug\",\"attributes\":[{\"kind\":\"attempts\",\"attempts\":1}]}"
```
Checked redis message, looks like the "completeExecution" message of current running execution may be related to re-order.  But we have no idea why it pops out the oldest waiting execution and pushes it back. 
```
{"kind":"completeExecution","executionType":"PIPELINE","executionId":"01F0WQV6WFRXCS2JQ5C8X043WP","application":"issuedebug","attributes":[{"kind":"attempts","attempts":3}]}
{"kind":"runTask","executionType":"PIPELINE","executionId":"01F0WQV6WFRXCS2JQ5C8X043WP","application":"issuedebug","stageId":"01F0WQV6WTS33MK59K55FBEQ3S","taskId":"1","taskType":"com.netflix.spinnaker.orca.pipeline.tasks.WaitTask","attributes":[{"kind":"attempts","attempts":1}],"ackTimeoutMs":600000}
```

We met this issue since 2019 (previous issue https://github.com/spinnaker/spinnaker/issues/4587. ) Now it still exists in 1.21, even latest 1.25. We also tried mysql as queue,  not working. 


### Steps to Reproduce:
1. create one pipeline, with two wait stages as two branches. One wait stage1 set like 10 secs, the other wait stage2 set 300 secs
2. disable concurrent execution of this pipeline
3. run this pipeline 5 times, to make sure one running and 4 waiting. The 4 waiting executions should follow FIFO in redis queue at the very beginning (with attempt=1)
4. When wait stage1 complete but waitStage2 is still running, the "kind":"completeExecution" will be created in orca message. 
5. Now monitor the waiting 4 executions from both UI and redis queue, you can see the re-order. 

### Additional Details:


---

issue.title: Spin CLI cached token not updating (stopped after 10 redirects)
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

Hello.

I'm using the `spin` CLI with cacheToken configuration.

This is the configuration I'm starting with:

```
gate:
  endpoint: <my-own-spinnaker-gate>
auth:
  enabled: true
  IgnoreCertErrors: false
  oauth2:
    authUrl: https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/v2/auth
    tokenUrl: https://www.googleapis.com/oauth2/v4/token
    cachedToken:
      access_token: ************
      refresh_token: ************
      token_type: bearer
    scopes:
      - email
      - profile
```

After the first `spin` command, the config file is changed to:
```
Auth:
  Basic: null
  Enabled: true
  GoogleServiceAccount: null
  Iap: null
  IgnoreCertErrors: false
  Ldap: null
  OAuth2:
    AuthUrl: https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/v2/auth
    CachedToken:
      access_token: ***********
      expiry: "0001-01-01T00:00:00Z"
      refresh_token: ***********
      token_type: bearer
    ClientId: ""
    ClientSecret: ""
    Scopes:
    - email
    - profile
    TokenUrl: https://www.googleapis.com/oauth2/v4/token
  X509: null
Gate:
  Endpoint: <my-own-spinnaker-gate>
```

After some time all commands just stop working and I have to refresh my access token manually.

All commands I execute results in this error:
```
Could not reach Gate, please ensure it is running. Failing.
Get https://<my-own-spinnaker-gate>/login: stopped after 10 redirects
```

I'm using this [documentation](https://spinnaker.io/docs/setup/other_config/spin/#access-and-refresh-token) as reference.

### Environment:

Spinnaker version: 1.26.7
Spin version: 1.22.0
Environment: Spinnaker running on GKE

### Steps to Reproduce:

- Create the config file
- Set token and refresh token
- Wait for the token expiration
- Execute the spin command again

issue.title: ECS caching cycle fails when an active ECS service exists with taskSets
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
The caching cycle of an ECS account is failing to complete when an ECS service exists in an ACTIVE state with taskSets definition. 

### Cloud Provider(s):
AWS

### Environment:
Spinnaker 1.26 in AWS EKS

### Feature Area:
ECS provider

### Description:
Following the code [here](https://github.com/spinnaker/clouddriver/blob/0a1405b937a8b45240c53abac977a103cca45a8c/clouddriver-ecs/src/main/java/com/netflix/spinnaker/clouddriver/ecs/provider/agent/TaskDefinitionCachingAgent.java#L83-L116) Spinnaker lists all the available ECS services in the configured region(s). Then it describes the service to retrieve the taskDefinitionArn and finally if the task definition doesnt exist in the cache (as it is immutable) describes the taskDefinition to be cached. 

When a service is defined with taskSets Spinnaker retrieves an empty TaskDefinitionArn which doesnt ignore and tries to describe it. Causing this failure:

> com.amazonaws.services.ecs.model.InvalidParameterException: Task Definition can not be blank. (Service: AmazonECS; Status Code: 400; Error Code: InvalidParameterException; Request ID: fcf39ec3-0e98-48f3-bb40-8b6ab19a7be5; Proxy: null)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.handleErrorResponse(AmazonHttpClient.java:1862)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.handleServiceErrorResponse(AmazonHttpClient.java:1415)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.executeOneRequest(AmazonHttpClient.java:1384)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.executeHelper(AmazonHttpClient.java:1154)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.doExecute(AmazonHttpClient.java:811)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.executeWithTimer(AmazonHttpClient.java:779)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.execute(AmazonHttpClient.java:753)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.access(AmazonHttpClient.java:713)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.execute(AmazonHttpClient.java:695)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.execute(AmazonHttpClient.java:559)
	at com.amazonaws.http.AmazonHttpClient.execute(AmazonHttpClient.java:539)
	at com.amazonaws.services.ecs.AmazonECSClient.doInvoke(AmazonECSClient.java:4668)
	at com.amazonaws.services.ecs.AmazonECSClient.invoke(AmazonECSClient.java:4635)
	at com.amazonaws.services.ecs.AmazonECSClient.invoke(AmazonECSClient.java:4624)
	at com.amazonaws.services.ecs.AmazonECSClient.executeDescribeTaskDefinition(AmazonECSClient.java:1759)
	at com.amazonaws.services.ecs.AmazonECSClient.describeTaskDefinition(AmazonECSClient.java:1727)
	at com.netflix.spinnaker.clouddriver.ecs.provider.agent.TaskDefinitionCachingAgent.getItems(TaskDefinitionCachingAgent.java:109)
	at com.netflix.spinnaker.clouddriver.ecs.provider.agent.AbstractEcsCachingAgent.loadData(AbstractEcsCachingAgent.java:100)
	at com.netflix.spinnaker.clouddriver.ecs.provider.agent.TaskDefinitionCachingAgent.loadData(TaskDefinitionCachingAgent.java:42)
	at com.netflix.spinnaker.cats.agent.CachingAgent.executeAgentWithoutStore(CachingAgent.java:87)
	at com.netflix.spinnaker.cats.agent.CachingAgent.executeAgent(CachingAgent.java:77)
	at com.netflix.spinnaker.cats.sql.cluster.AgentExecutionAction.execute(SqlClusteredAgentScheduler.kt:332)
	at com.netflix.spinnaker.cats.sql.cluster.AgentJob.run(SqlClusteredAgentScheduler.kt:351)
	at java.base/java.util.concurrent.Executors.call(Executors.java:515)
	at java.base/java.util.concurrent.FutureTask.run(FutureTask.java:264)
	at java.base/java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor.runWorker(ThreadPoolExecutor.java:1128)
	at java.base/java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor.run(ThreadPoolExecutor.java:628)
	at java.base/java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:829)

The caching cycle never completes for this account causing deploy failures.
### Steps to Reproduce:

1.  Create a taskSet service definition in an ECS cluster in an AWS account
2. Onboard an ECS account  in Spinnaker

issue.title: `hal --ready` CLI command can not deserialize Halyard health check response
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

The `hal --ready` command can not deserialize health check response returned by Halyard when a `groups` field is included in said health check.

### Cloud Provider(s):

Kubernetes.

### Environment:

We use the Helm chart provided by `OpsMx/spinnaker-helm` version 2.2.6 to deploy Spinnaker version 1.26.7 and Halyard version 1.45.0 (which is using [this](https://console.cloud.google.com/artifacts/docker/spinnaker-community/us/docker/halyard/sha256:d9356a83806d10460fc66590e7dd7d67ffe080892607d14e9df2b0bae395caa0) Docker image).

### Feature Area:

Halyard, `hal` CLI.

### Description:

During efforts yesterday to upgrade Halyard from 1.44.1 to 1.45.0 we noticed a change in the `/health` endpoint response body from our Halyard pod. Previously, running the following command inside said pod returned:

```bash
$ curl http://spinnaker-spinnaker-halyard:8064/health 
{
  "status" : "UP"
}
```

Now with version 1.45.0 it returns:

```bash
$ curl http://spinnaker-spinnaker-halyard:8064/health 
{
  "status" : "UP",
  "groups" : [ "liveness", "readiness" ]
}
```

This causes the `hal --ready` command to error as it [expects](https://github.com/spinnaker/halyard/blob/v1.45.0/halyard-cli/src/main/java/com/netflix/spinnaker/halyard/cli/services/v1/DaemonService.java#L40) a `Map<String, String>`:

```bash
hal --ready
! ERROR
  com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.exc.MismatchedInputException: Cannot
  deserialize value of type `java.lang.String` from Array value (token
  `JsonToken.START_ARRAY`)
at [Source: (retrofit.ExceptionCatchingTypedInput$ExceptionCatchingInputStream);
  line: 3, column: 14] (through reference chain:
  java.util.LinkedHashMap["groups"])
? Try the command again with the --debug flag.
```

This stalls deployment with the `OpsMx/spinnaker-helm` chart linked before and prevents us from upgrading further.

I would expect `hal` CLI to be able to parse this response as it only uses the `status` field's value to determine healthiness.

### Steps to Reproduce:

Unfortunately I could not narrow down the (Spring) configuration to have Halyard return `"groups" : [ "liveness", "readiness" ]` in its `/health` response body by running the Docker image linked before locally.

issue.title: Halyard attempts to install the packages in the BOM every single time `hal deploy apply` is run
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

Halyard should only run the bash install script once per Spinnaker version change and not every single time the deployment is applied.

### Cloud Provider(s):

AWS

### Environment:

- Ubuntu 22.04 LTS VM
- Halyard 1.50.0
- Spinnaker 1.28.1

### Feature Area:

Halyard

### Description:

#### Expected Behaviour

The `.hal/default/install.sh` should only be run the very first time the BOM for each Spinnaker version need to be installed.  For example, I initially set my Spinnaker version to `1.27.0` and run `hal deploy apply`, then the BOM for `1.27.0` should be installed once and once only.  If I then edit the Spinnaker version and change it to `1.28.1`, and run `hal deploy apply` then it should run the install script again to install the new BOM for the new Spinnaker version, but only run it the first time the new Spinnaker version is applied and not every single time `hal deploy apply` is run thereafter.

#### Actual Behaviour

When running `hal deploy apply`, the `.hal/default/install.sh` is run every single time the deployment is applied, which wastes a lot of unnecessary time and CPU cycles.

### Steps to Reproduce:

1. Install Halyard 1.50.0.
2. Configure Spinnaker version and persistent storage backend.
3. Run `hal deploy apply`.
4. Use `hal` command to edit some arbitrary configuration.
5. Run `hal deploy apply` again.
6. Observe the BOM attempting to be installed each time, even though it is already installed.

### Additional Details:

None

issue.title: CloudBuild private worker pool not found
issue.body:
I'm trying to run a GCB (Google Cloud Build) step as a text build definition source, but when executing the stage it errors.

Example manifest:

```
steps:
  - args:
      - '-c'
      - 'echo hello'
    entrypoint: bash
    name: gcr.io/cloud-builders/git
options:
  pool:
    name: projects/PROJECT_NAME/locations/REGION/workerPools/WORKER_POOL_NAME
```

So I'm trying to run this GCB using a private worker pool (names have been obfuscated) which does exist, but when running via Spinnaker results in the following error (found via the execution source):

```
"errors" : [ {
    "domain" : "global",
    "message" : "workerpool not found: \"PATH_TO_WORKER_POOL"",
    "reason" : "notFound"
 ```
 
Using gcloud locally the manifest runs perfectly fine.

After some Googling it would appear that some clients need to support overriding the region (or endpoint) in which GCB runs: https://issuetracker.google.com/issues/193685195?pli=1

I'm my specific use case I need to run the manifest as a text based source so that I can inject Spinnaker parameters, which I don't think is possible when using a pre-defined trigger. 


Any help would be appreciated.

issue.title: Uneven passwordFile/usernamePasswordFile support across services/objects
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
Spinnaker services and objects have uneven support for passwordFile and usernamePasswordFile

The artifacts block only supports usernamePasswordFile,
https://docs.armory.io/armory-enterprise/installation/armory-operator/op-manifest-reference/artifact/#account-parameters-6

While the Concourse / Jenkins CI configs only support password:
https://docs.armory.io/armory-enterprise/installation/armory-operator/op-manifest-reference/ci/

As it stands, the latter's lack of passwordFile support requires users to store exposed passwords in git or store the config entirely (or the -local.yml variant) in vault instead of just the passwords alone.

### Cloud Provider(s):
Kubernetes

### Environment:
We utilize a K8S Spinnaker deployment, where clouddriver for example has a Vault init container that mounts a /vault/ directory that we set passwordFile (where available) to point to.

### Feature Area:
Igor / Clouddriver

### Description:
Expected:
Ability to use passwordFile evenly across services/objects.

Actual:
passwordFile is only supported in a few objects/services.

### Steps to Reproduce:
Configure a Spinnaker artifact to use passwordFile, it won't work.

issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
I'm working my way through setting up red/black deployments through a small test app. That part works but when destroying an old rs from the cluster orca throws a `com.netflix.spinnaker.orca.clouddriver.pipeline.servergroup.support.TargetServerGroup$NotFoundException: Unable to locate replicaSet redblack-v002 in staging/staging/replicaSet redblack`

### Cloud Provider(s):
kubernetes

### Environment:
development

### Feature Area:
Unknown

### Description:
Deleting an old replicaset in a cluster causes an exception (see summary & steps). I paired down my testing to the bare minimum and I feel I'm missing something obvious. The issue appears to be cloud driver not knowing about the rs but its visible in the UI but clouddriver throws not a single log entry on the destroy action.

I verified `serviceaccount` I'm using has `cluster-admin` permissions so clouddriver should be able to see it/does see it(?)

### Steps to Reproduce:
My service definition:
```
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  annotations:
    artifact.spinnaker.io/location: development
    artifact.spinnaker.io/name: redblack
    artifact.spinnaker.io/type: kubernetes/service
    artifact.spinnaker.io/version: ""
    moniker.spinnaker.io/application: internal
    moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: service redblack
    traffic.spinnaker.io/load-balancers: '["service redblack"]'
  labels:
    app: redblack
    app.kubernetes.io/managed-by: spinnaker
    app.kubernetes.io/name: internal
  name: redblack
  namespace: development
spec:
  externalTrafficPolicy: Cluster
  ipFamilies:
  - IPv4
  ipFamilyPolicy: SingleStack
  ports:
  - nodePort: 31653
    port: 80
    protocol: TCP
    targetPort: 8000
  selector:
    frontedBy: redblack
  sessionAffinity: None
  type: LoadBalancer
```

My replicaset:
```
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: ReplicaSet
metadata:
  labels:
    app: redblack
  name: redblack
  namespace: development
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      service: redblack
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        service: redblack
    spec:
      containers:
        - image: lwander/spin-kub-v2-demo
          name: primary
          ports:
            - containerPort: 8000
          readinessProbe:
            httpGet:
              path: /
              port: 8000
```

Deploy the rs a couple of times, which is does successfully:
```
~/ k get rs -l=app=redblack
NAME                 DESIRED   CURRENT   READY   AGE
redblack-v001   1         1         1       18h
redblack-v002   1         1         1       17h
redblack-v003   1         1         1       17h
```

Go into the Clusters view in deck and attempt to destroy any of the older versions (v001,2)

### Additional Details:
Full request and stack trace:
```

issue.title: Failed to extract artifact: Gzip-compressed data is corrupt (CRC32 error) in Bake Manifest (Kustomize renderer)
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
Getting below error in Bake Manifest stage

```
Exception ( Create Bake )

Failed to extract artifact: Gzip-compressed data is corrupt (CRC32 error)
```

### Cloud Provider(s):
OVH (on-premise install)

### Environment:
Kubernetes
Spinnaker v1.27

### Feature Area:


### Description:
I recently deployed my Spinnaker instance. After configuring Halyard to setup gitrepo (attached to my Github account) and using the Bake Manifest stage to render my Kustomize config, i'm not able to get it working. Double checked many times the setup with other Spinnaker-managed projects (on other provider), but couldn't find anything different. 

### Steps to Reproduce:
1. Create Application
2. Add pipeline with Bake Manifest
3. Create new artifact from execution context and select my pre-configured gitrepo (attached to Github) and Kustomize as the renderer.

### Additional Details:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/34267739/177336869-1a83c2b8-980c-4cff-bf18-7f9d5ff5e9ec.png)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/34267739/177336997-db1a7e61-3f00-4e25-af9d-8c74c3e2a220.png)

issue.title: CustomResource Not Showing as Available for Deletion in Delete or Patch Manifest Stage
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
After adding Custom Resources via Halyard to Kubernetes accounts, the Custom Resource names do not show up in the drop down as available for deletion in either a Delete or Patch manifest type stage. 

### Cloud Provider(s):
Kubernetes

### Environment:
Spinnaker running in Kubernetes v1.23.7, version 1.26.6 of Spinnaker. Leveraging Halyard to deploy Spinnaker into the Kubernetes cluster. 

### Feature Area:
UI

### Description:
Clouddriver sees the custom resources and caches them properly, the appropriate Custom Resource Type is available in the drop down in the Patch Manifest or Delete Manifest type stages. But the name of the given Custom Resource does not show up as available in the drop down in the UI. 

The resource name can be entered manually and the Patch Manifest or Delete Manifest stage works appropriately. Presumably this is just a UI/Deck issue when listing the Custom Resource. 

Expected:

The name of the Custom Resource should be available in the drop down after adding the Custom resources to the Spinnaker Kubernetes account configuration to be selected for Delete or Patch

### Steps to Reproduce:
- Add Custom Resource of any Kind to Kubernetes Account in Spinnaker
- Create a pipeline with a Delete or Patch Manifest Stage
- Select Account, Namespace, Selector of Static Target, and Kind in the stage configuration
- The Name drop down will be empty when the Custom resource Kind is selected.

issue.title: Allow sensitive values to be used in preconfigured webhooks without showing up in the execution context
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

Preconfigured webhooks may contain sensitive values (like credentials to authenticate with the webhook endpoint) with an expectation of privacy since those values are not displayed in Deck when adding the stage to a pipeline.  However, as mentioned [here](https://github.com/spinnaker/orca/pull/1329#issue-119663993) those values still are available in the execution context.  

### Feature Area: 

Webhook stages

### Description:

It would be helpful to be able to keep the values from the preconfigured webhook stage that aren't needed in Deck from being returned.   This could be the default behavior, but in cases where the values aren't sensitive it can be valuable to still have them available for troubleshooting.   Another option would be to allow the preconfigured stage to declare what values are sensitive:

```yaml
      customHeaders:
        X-Api-Key:
          - <newrelic-api-key>
        Content-Type:
          - application/json
      # Proposed change
      sensitiveHeaders:
        - X-Api-Key
      sensitivePayload: true
```
(I'm assuming that only headers or the payload would be expected to contain sensitive data)

### Additional details:

Relates to https://github.com/spinnaker/orca/pull/1329

issue.title: Default namespace should be different and adjustable for each application/pipeline
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
Namespace in Bake Stage should be used as a default namespace for running pipeline, if namespace is not explicitly mentioned in helm chart templates.

### Steps to Reproduce:
We simultaneously deploy 3 different parts:
- our own helm chart to `NAMESPACE A` 
- few templates to `NAMESPACE B`
- third party helm chart packed in .tgz with no mention of namespace at all

As you can see, the problem cannot be solved with `namespaceOverride` feature in Deploy Stage.
I choose namespace in Bake Stage for `NAMESPACE A` to expect deploy everything there, if it is not specified otherwise.

When we deploy this setup, the overall result will be:
- my app will be in `NAMESPACE A`
- few templates will be in `NAMESPACE B`
- third party helm chart will be in `NAMESPACE SPINNAKER`

The third party helm chart are expected to be installed in the same namespace as my app (`NAMESPACE A`).
We cannot modify third party helm charts in .tgz and unfortunately it contains templates without `{{ .Release.Namespace }}` parameter, so the bake stage with Namespace feature do nothing.
Default namespace `SPINNAKER` it is not practical. 

IMHO, we should be able to choose default namespace at the pipeline level.

### Additional Details:
Spinnaker 1.28.1

issue.title: Feature to use different service accounts per hal accounts
issue.body:
Related to https://github.com/spinnaker/spinnaker/issues/6495 issue. 
Could we please consider adding a feature to be able to use different service accounts to connect to clusters. As this could be security issues using a single service account for all the clusters.

~/hal/hal config provider kubernetes account add cluster1
--provider-version v2
--kubeconfig-file /home/spinnaker/.hal/default/credentials/cluster1
--live-manifest-calls true
--only-spinnaker-managed true
**--service-account-name cluster1** 

Clouddriver should be able to use the service-account-name to connect to specifc hal accounts

issue.title: Stage with continuePipeline = true and multiple subtasks doesn't show real failure reason
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
When stage with multiple tasks (e.g. `jenkins` task) fails at the first task and stage has `        "continuePipeline": true`, then stage continues to execute next subtasks. As a result, pipeline UI shows error of last subtask, which is misleading.


### Cloud Provider(s):
AWS, Kubernetes(for Spinnaker itself)

### Environment:
Spinnaker (v1.26.6), orca:2.20.3-20210630022216


### Feature Area:
Pipelines

### Description:
My pipeline has `jenkins` stage. This stage has multiple subtasks:
- Start Jenkins Job
- Wait For Jenkins Job Start
- Monitor Jenkins Job
- Get Build Properties
- Get Build Artifacts

We also have set "continuePipeline: true" for jenkins stage, so we can perform some action after this stage fails.
The problem occurs when "Start Jenkins Job" fails for some reason - either Jenkins is down, or jenkins job parameters are configured incorrectly and Jenkins returns HTTP 400. Then subsequent tasks are executed and obviously fail, because required parameters are not filled in the stage context (e.g "Start Jenkins Job" did not fill `buildNumber` required by subsequent stages)

As a result Pipeline UI shows misleading error from the last task:
```
Exception

 Path parameter "buildNumber" value must not be null.
```

instead of real root cause - error from first task telling about incorrectly configured parameter for jenkins job (I redacted this message a bit):
```
Exception ( Start Jenkins Job )

__INCORRECT_VALUE__ is not a valid choice for __PARAMETER_NAME__. Valid choices are: __CORRECT_VALUE__
```


### Steps to Reproduce:
- Create jenkins pipeline with `choice` parameter: https://www.jenkins.io/doc/book/pipeline/syntax/#parameters
- Create Spinnaker pipeline that contains `jenkins` stage calling previously created jenkins job/pipeline:
    - Configure `jenkins` stage to use incorrect parameter (value not specified by `choices` in Jenkinsfile)
    - Set `If stage fails: ignore the failure` (` "continuePipeline": true` in JSON representation)
- Run the pipeline

#### Actual result

Stage fails with:
```
Exception

Path parameter "buildNumber" value must not be null.
```

All subtasks are executed:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15031715/156006399-4cb32833-0b0d-4914-a8e6-3554fc31db12.png)


#### Expected result:

Stage fails with
```
Exception ( Start Jenkins Job )

__INCORRECT_VALUE__ is not a valid choice for __PARAMETER_NAME__. Valid choices are: __CORRECT_VALUE__
```

Subsequent subtasks are not executed:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15031715/156006441-98e39533-e9ba-4758-9773-b692134691ad.png)


### Additional Details:

-  When I set `continuePipeline: false`, then jenkins stage displays correct error from `Start Jenkins Job` and subsequent task are not executed. However that's not acceptable workaround, because then I can't run subsequent stages that contain error handling.

-  I think the root of the problem is mapping of STAGE behaviour to TASK behaviour here:
https://github.com/spinnaker/orca/blob/730b076879a517cd0307f55a15ca59ae00a260d5/orca-kotlin/src/main/kotlin/com/netflix/spinnaker/orca/ext/Stage.kt#L131-L137

issue.title: Feature request - use Namespace as a deployment target rather than a bake value
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

Helm builds are not immutable.

Deployed helm charts cannot include dependencies without alteration.

### Cloud Provider(s):

All

### Environment:

Kubernetes deploys

### Feature Area:

Chart baking

### Description:

Deployment to a target Kubernetes namespace is achieved by adding {{ .Release.Namespace }} to each template, enabling Spinnaker to add the predetermined namespace into the templates at the bake stage.

This presents numerous issues:

1. You have to add Release.Namespace to each chart

2. Having to modify third party chart dependencies to add Release.Namespace to their charts too (and therefore not being able to consume these dependencies without alteration)

3. Spinnaker builds are not immutable.

So... feature request - could you treat the namespace as a _target_ for any given pipeline deploy, rather than a _value_ that is baked into the charts

i.e.

helm upgrade --install release-name chart -n TARGET_NAMESPACE

Doing so would make the helm builds immutable and would remove the necessity to alter charts & their dependencies.

Templates without {{ .Release.Namespace }} interestingly do not end up in the default namespace - which you'd expect if no namespace was provided as a target during deploy - they end up in 'foo-spinnaker ' . This means that spinnaker _is_ providing a namespace during deploy, just not the namespace specified in the pipeline config.   This to me seems like a bug.


### Steps to Reproduce:

Try to deploy a  helm chart and again with dependencies

### Additional Details:

---

**_Please delete the instructions below this line prior to submitting_**

issue.title: Kustomise engine fails to render CronJob
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

When using `Bake (Manifest)` to build CronJob with overlay, instead of adding properties to container, they get overwritten. This is not what standalone/kubectl Kustomize does.

### Environment:

Spinnaker 1.26.7, KUSTOMIZE render engine, artifact from execution context.

Local kubectl version:
Client Version: version.Info{Major:"1", Minor:"24", GitVersion:"v1.24.2", GitCommit:"f66044f4361b9f1f96f0053dd46cb7dce5e990a8", GitTreeState:"clean", BuildDate:"2022-06-15T14:22:29Z", GoVersion:"go1.18.3", Compiler:"gc", Platform:"linux/amd64"}
Kustomize Version: v4.5.4


### Description:

Standalone Kustomize output:

```
apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: CronJob
metadata:
  name: cronName
spec:
  jobTemplate:
    spec:
      template:
        spec:
          containers:
          - image: hello-world
            imagePullPolicy: Always
            name: containerName
  schedule: '* * * * *'

```

Spinnaker baked output:

```
apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: CronJob
metadata:
  name: cronName
spec:
  jobTemplate:
    spec:
      template:
        spec:
          containers:
          - imagePullPolicy: Always
            name: containerName
  schedule: '* * * * *'
```

### Steps to Reproduce:

base/kustomization.yaml:
```
resources:
  - cronjob.yaml
```

base/cronjob.yaml:
```
apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: CronJob
metadata:
  name: cronName
spec:
  jobTemplate:
    spec:
      template:
        spec:
          containers:
          - name: containerName

issue.title: Using non-alphanumeric characters in an SSL cert passphrase prevents deck from loading.
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

Using non-alphanumeric characters in an SSL cert passphrase prevents deck from loading, getting stuck in a `CrashLoopBackOff` state.

### Environment:

K8s distributed

### Feature Area:
Deck
SSL

### Description:

When using the following password for an ssl cert:

```
export DECK_KEY_PASSWORD='1?Zu7,i6%4@m0]&5>j9(q3.'
```

the `/etc/apache2/passphrase` file generated in the `deck` container of the `spin-deck-*-*` pod is incorrect:

```
#!/usr/bin/env bash

if [ -n "1?Zu7,i6%4@m0]{%PASSPHRASE%}5>j9(q3." ]; then
  echo "1?Zu7,i6%4@m0]{%PASSPHRASE%}5>j9(q3."
fi
```

This password was generated from a PWM that uses all characters in the generated passwords. Ideally the docs would warn against using non-alphanumeric characters in passwords if this is expected behavior or unavoidable.
it appears to be the `&` character in particular that is causing the issue.


This is easily worked around but it took me non-significant amount of time to figure the issue out, and i imagine others could encounter the same situation.
Thanks for your time.

issue.title: %252C isn't un-escaped in spinnaker UI while %252c is
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
`https://spinnaker_hostname/#/applications/myapp/executions?pipeline=Deploy%20something%252C%20otherthing`
Resolves to `PIPELINE: Deploy something%2C otherthing`
while
`https://spinnaker_hostname/#/applications/myapp/executions?pipeline=Deploy%20something%252c%20otherthing`
Resolves to `PIPELINE: Deploy something, otherthing`

One issue is that double-escaping is needed for comma `,` but not for space ` ` character.
Another issue is that `%2C` doesn't work while `%2c` works.

https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986#section-2.1
>    The uppercase hexadecimal digits 'A' through 'F' are equivalent to
   the lowercase digits 'a' through 'f', respectively.  If two URIs
   differ only in the case of hexadecimal digits used in percent-encoded
   octets, they are equivalent.  For consistency, URI producers and
   normalizers should use uppercase hexadecimal digits for all percent-

issue.title: Deck assumes pipeline templates are only stored in Front50
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
When editing a pipeline sourced from a template using the "Configure Template" button, the changes error out since it can't find the pipeline template in front50.


### Cloud Provider(s):
AWS, Kubernetes(for Spinnaker itself)

### Environment:
Spinnaker 1.26.6, Deck 3.7.3-20211116020328

### Feature Area:
Pipeline Templates/ UI

### Description:
We use an http artifact account to grab our pipeline template JSONs from a webserver. This works quite well when referencing it in the pipeline JSON like:
```
"template": {
    "artifactAccount": "http",
    "name": "myTemplate",
    "reference": "https://example.com:443/spinnaker-templates/myTemplate.json",
    "type": "http/file"
  },
```
However when trying to update the pipeline variables via the "Configure Template" button, the updates are not saved and you see an error 
``` 
Could not generate pipeline from provided template configuration.

Error: No message provided
```

In the browser network tab we can see that the request to `https://my-spinnanker-api.com/v2/pipelineTemplates/plan` uses the below artifactAccount

```
{
    "artifactAccount": "front50ArtifactCredentials",
    "reference": "spinnaker://https://example.com:443/spinnaker-templates/myTemplate.json",
    "type": "front50/pipelineTemplate"
}
```
The expectation is that the request uses the same artifact account as the template block and successfully updates the template variables.  Note that updating the variables via "Edit Pipeline as JSON" has the desired effect and leaves the pipeline template artifact alone.


### Steps to Reproduce:
1. host a pipeline template json on a webserver
2. Create a pipeline with template block like:
"template": {
    "artifactAccount": "http",
    "name": "myTemplate",
    "reference": "https://example.com:443/spinnaker-templates/myTemplate.json",
    "type": "http/file"
  },
3. In the UI, go to configure pipeline
4. Click configure template
5. Edit one of the pipeline variables
6. Save changes
7. Notice error message and the pipeline fails to update.

issue.title: Application prefix permissions don't work with Kubernetes account + SAML authentication
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:
Application prefix permissions don't work with Kubernetes + SAML authentication (not sure if the SAML authentication is relevant)

### Cloud Provider(s):
Kubernetes

### Environment:
Spinnaker is installed on a k8s cluster using this helm chart (using Spinnaker version 1.26.7): https://github.com/OpsMx/spinnaker-helm
The Spinnaker components versions are the following:
```
Spinnaker: 1.26.7
Halyard: 1.41.0
Fiat: 1.16.0
Clouddriver: 8.0.4
Deck: 3.7.2
Front50: 0.27.1
Gate: 1.22.2
Igor: 1.16.0
Orca: 2.20.3
Rosco: 0.25.0
Echo: 2.17.1
```
I've setup Spinnaker to use SAML authentication/authorization with Azure AD groups.

These are the permissions for the default Kubernetes account (taken from `hal config` command):
```yaml
name: default
version: 1.26.7
providers:
  kubernetes:
    enabled: true
    accounts:
    - name: default
      requiredGroupMembership: []
      permissions:
        READ:
        - cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c
        - 7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138
        WRITE:
        - cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c
        - 7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138
      dockerRegistries:
      - accountName: dockerhub
        namespaces: []
      providerVersion: V2
      context: default
      configureImagePullSecrets: true
      serviceAccount: true
      cacheThreads: 1
      namespaces: []
      omitNamespaces:
      - kube-system
      - kube-public
      kinds: []
      omitKinds: []
      customResources: []
      cachingPolicies: []
      rawResourcesEndpointConfig:
        kindExpressions: []
        omitKindExpressions: []
      oAuthScopes: []
      onlySpinnakerManaged: false
```


### Feature Area:
Application permissions using prefixes

### Description:
Hello, I'm new to Spinnaker and I've been trying to get the prefix application permissions work but I am not able to. No applications are shown in the UI although they match the prefix. Below the SAML group `cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c` is an admin group, the issue is with users from the `7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138` group.

Test 1 is my desired setup. Test 2 is a modification of Test 1 with capitalized application name (after looking into the Fiat source code). And Test 3 just shows that if I don't use the prefixes but exact application name, things work (but that isn't what I want)

## Test 1 - using a prefix, application with lower case - doesn't work
This is my desired setup.

The contents of the `fiat-local.yml` file is this:
```yaml
fiat:
  executeFallback: WRITE
  restrictApplicationCreation: true
  admin:
    roles:
    - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
auth:
  permissions:
    provider:
      application: aggregate
    source:
      application:
        front50:
          enabled: true
        prefix:
          enabled: true
          prefixes:
          - prefix: '*'
            permissions:
              WRITE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              CREATE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              EXECUTE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              READ:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
          - prefix: 'myapp*'
            permissions:
              READ:
              - '7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138'
```

I deployed a test k8s deployment inside the default Kubernetes account (where Spinnaker is installed) with appropriate moniker annotations for `myapplication` application:
```yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: spinnakertest-nginx-deployment-01
  namespace: spinnakertest-ns
  labels:
    app: nginx-01
  annotations:
    moniker.spinnaker.io/application: myapplication
    moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: nginx-01
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: nginx-01
      annotations:
        moniker.spinnaker.io/application: myapplication
        moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx-01
        image: nginx:1.14.2
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
```

But the users from the SAML group `7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138` can't see the app in the Spinnaker UI:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15890495/183103507-d1fff101-9137-46bb-a037-f62a81c349fd.png)

## Test 2 - using a prefix, application with upper case - doesn't work

I went through Fiat's code and found that the prefix check uses a toUpperCase(): https://github.com/spinnaker/fiat/blob/v1.16.0/fiat-roles/src/main/java/com/netflix/spinnaker/fiat/providers/ResourcePrefixPermissionSource.java#L70
```java
public boolean contains(T resource) {
  if (isFullApplicationName) {
    return prefix.equalsIgnoreCase(resource.getName());
  }

  String prefixWithoutStar = prefix.substring(0, prefix.length() - 1);
  prefixWithoutStar = prefixWithoutStar.toUpperCase();
  return resource.getName().startsWith(prefixWithoutStar);
}
```

So I changed my test k8s deployment so that the application is with capital letters:
```yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: spinnakertest-nginx-deployment-01
  namespace: spinnakertest-ns
  labels:
    app: nginx-01
  annotations:
    moniker.spinnaker.io/application: MYAPPLICATION
    moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: nginx-01
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: nginx-01
      annotations:
        moniker.spinnaker.io/application: MYAPPLICATION
        moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx-01
        image: nginx:1.14.2
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
```

This time the users from the SAML group `7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138` can see the application in the Spinnaker UI, but when I go into the application details, no details/server groups are shown:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15890495/183103728-db10b549-61db-4434-983b-22a699c7928a.png)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15890495/183103852-6c835f55-f436-4dc5-a9d7-7e0a4ec3f020.png)

## Test 3 - using exact application name (not using a prefix), application with lower case - works
This works, but it's not a desired setup - the prefixes aren't used.

When I change the prefix application permissions to contain the whole name without `*`, then everything works fine - I can see the application in the Spinnaker UI, and the details/server groups show fine as well:
`fiat-local.yaml`:
```yaml
fiat:
  executeFallback: WRITE
  restrictApplicationCreation: true
  admin:
    roles:
    - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'         
auth:
  permissions:
    provider:
      application: aggregate
    source:
      application:
        front50:
          enabled: true
        prefix:
          enabled: true
          prefixes:
          - prefix: '*'
            permissions:
              WRITE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              CREATE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              EXECUTE:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
              READ:
              - 'cd08ef25-6d04-47f6-ae7a-7181f4dcb99c'
          - prefix: 'myapplication'
            permissions:
              READ:
              - '7007ad00-2eaf-470c-bae2-f85b2a823138'
```
Test deployment:
```yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: spinnakertest-nginx-deployment-01
  namespace: spinnakertest-ns
  labels:
    app: nginx-01
  annotations:
    moniker.spinnaker.io/application: myapplication
    moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: nginx-01
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: nginx-01
      annotations:
        moniker.spinnaker.io/application: myapplication
        moniker.spinnaker.io/cluster: mycluster
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx-01
        image: nginx:1.14.2
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
```
Result:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15890495/183104004-d46064d2-46bd-4b47-806c-4a3993b5fd4f.png)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15890495/183104155-845d0c7d-04b7-4bbb-af7d-945b58da308b.png)

That's why I thought there might be a bug with the prefix permissions (possibly when used together with applications in a Kubernetes account + SAML authentication) - maybe the [above code snippet](https://github.com/spinnaker/fiat/blob/v1.16.0/fiat-roles/src/main/java/com/netflix/spinnaker/fiat/providers/ResourcePrefixPermissionSource.java#L70) in Fiat should be changed so case is ignored when using `String.startsWith()`, instead of having a `toUpperCase()` on just the prefix?

Or maybe I haven't configured the prefix permissions correctly?

I haven't tested it with Spinnaker 1.27.0 (Fiat version 1.28.4), because it doesn't work with the helm chart (for example these issues: https://github.com/spinnaker/spinnaker/issues/6655 , https://github.com/spinnaker/spinnaker/issues/6700 , also there are issues with the readiness probes), but I see Fiat v1.28.4 still has the same toUpperCase() code: https://github.com/spinnaker/fiat/blob/v1.28.4/fiat-roles/src/main/java/com/netflix/spinnaker/fiat/providers/ResourcePrefixPermissionSource.java#L71

### Steps to Reproduce:
Deploy Spinnaker in Kubernetes using the helm chart (https://github.com/OpsMx/spinnaker-helm). And use the above permission settings and test Kubernetes deployments (between the test cases delete the Kubernetes deployment before creating the new one to avoid leftover ReplicaSets with the old moniker application name - this adds additional issues). I'm not sure if SAML authentication/authorization is relevant.

issue.title: Clouddriver: stops syncing Docker registry at intermittent intervals
issue.body:
### Issue Summary:

Potentially related issue: #4780

Clouddriver will stop syncing with our Docker registry at intermittent intervals. There is no error message logged by Clouddriver, event after setting the log level to `TRACE`.

### Cloud Provider(s):

AWS EKS

### Environment:

- EKS v1.18
- Halyard 1.40.0
- Spinnaker 1.23.3
- Clouddriver 7.0.3

### Feature Area:

Clouddriver

### Description:

### Steps to Reproduce:

### Additional Details:

When working correctly, Clouddriver will output a info message stating that it is going to start describing the cached items in the registry, and follow up with the amount of ids and tags it grabs:

```
2020-12-14 07:01:10.838  INFO 1 --- [cutionAction-29] .d.r.p.a.DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent : Describing items in <docker-registry>/DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent[1/1]
2020-12-14 07:01:13.103  INFO 1 --- [cutionAction-29] .d.r.p.a.DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent : Caching 21174 tagged images in <docker-registry>/DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent[1/1]
2020-12-14 07:01:13.103  INFO 1 --- [cutionAction-29] .d.r.p.a.DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent : Caching 21174 image ids in <docker-registry>/DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent[1/1]
```

However, I've noticed that after Clouddriver stops syncing the registry, the cached tags and ids are not printing, and we only get the message from the describe call:
```
2020-12-13 08:09:57.750  INFO 1 --- [utionAction-116] .d.r.p.a.DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent : Describing items in <docker-registry>/DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent[1/1]
```
From this point onwards, Clouddriver will not sync with the registry until it (Clouddriver) has been restarted. Once it has been restarted, it will sync with the registry just fine until this intermittent failure occurs again.

It seems like if there is a problem here with Clouddriver proper, the offending code would be somewhere in the `buildCacheResult` method of the `DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent`: https://github.com/spinnaker/clouddriver/blob/874cef3644c826a1932d9670d59ccb77a19e19a2/clouddriver-docker/src/main/groovy/com/netflix/spinnaker/clouddriver/docker/registry/provider/agent/DockerRegistryImageCachingAgent.groovy#L135

I have also checked connectivity to our Docker registry during these outages, and I can connect to it just fine while this issue occurs with Clouddriver.

fix(pipelineTriggers): handle invalid constraint regexes (#1209)

* fix(pipelineTriggers): handle invalid constraint regexes

Currently, if a user accidentally configures a pipeline trigger with an
invalid regex for a constraint value, echo throws a
`PatternSyntaxException` any time it receives an event that should be
tested against the constraint.  As a result, all pipeline triggers using
the same trigger type & source/subscription will be non-functional, not
just the pipeline with the bad regex.

This patch catches `PatternSyntaxException`, logs an error about the bad
regex for troubleshooting purposes, and returns `false` such that the
bad regex will never match, allowing all other pipeline triggers to
continue functioning normally.

* fix(pipelineTriggers): improved logging for invalid constraint patterns
